Context

AllLife Bank is a US bank that has a growing customer base. The majority of these customers are liability customers (depositors) with varying sizes of deposits. The number of customers who are also borrowers (asset customers) is quite small, and the bank is interested in expanding this base rapidly to bring in more loan business and in the process, earn more through the interest on loans. In particular, the management wants to explore ways of converting its liability customers to personal loan customers (while retaining them as depositors).

A campaign that the bank ran last year for liability customers showed a healthy conversion rate of over 9% success. This has encouraged the retail marketing department to devise campaigns with better target marketing to increase the success ratio.

You as a Data Scientist at AllLife Bank have to build a model that will help the marketing department to identify the potential customers who have a higher probability of purchasing the loan.

Objective To predict whether a liability customer will buy personal loans, to understand which customer attributes are most significant in driving purchases, and to identify which segment of customers to target more.

Data Dictionary

ID: Customer ID

Age: Customers age in completed years

Experience: # years of professional experience

Income: Annual income of the customer (in thousand dollars)

ZIP Code: Home Address ZIP code.

Family: The family size of the customer

CCAvg: Average spending on credit cards per month (in thousand dollars)

Education: Education Level. 1: Undergrad; 2: Graduate;3: Advanced/Professional

Mortgage: Value of house mortgage if any. (in thousand dollars)

Personal_Loan: Did this customer accept the personal loan offered in the last campaign?

Securities_Account: Does the customer have a securities account with the bank?

CD_Account: Does the customer have a certificate of deposit (CD) account with the bank?

Online: Do customers use Internet banking facilities?

CreditCard: Does the customer use a credit card issued by any other Bank (excluding All Life Bank)?

In[24]:
categorical_cols = ['Family','Education','Personal_Loan','Securities_Account','CD_Account','Online','CreditCard']
target = 'Personal_Loan'

# Categorical vs Target (countplots + pie charts)
for col in categorical_cols:
    if col != target:
        plt.figure(figsize=(6,4))
        sns.countplot(data=df, x=col, hue=target, palette="Set1")
        plt.title(f'{col} vs {target} (Countplot)')
        plt.show()
        
        # Pie chart of target distribution for each category
        for val in df[col].unique():
            subset = df[df[col]==val][target].value_counts()
            plt.figure(figsize=(4,4))
            subset.plot.pie(autopct='%1.1f%%', colors=['lightblue','salmon'], startangle=90)
            plt.ylabel('')
            plt.title(f'{target} distribution for {col}={val}')
            plt.show()

Observations:

1. Family vs Personal Loan

Customers with family size = 1 or 2 are less likely to have taken a personal loan (loan acceptance rate around 78%).

The likelihood of taking a personal loan increases slightly for families with 3 or 4 members (loan acceptance around 1113%).

Overall, customers with larger family sizes tend to have higher chances of personal loan acceptance, possibly due to increased financial needs.

2. Education vs Personal Loan

Education level 1 (Undergraduate) customers have the lowest loan acceptance rate (45%).

Education level 2 (Graduate) customers show moderate acceptance (13%).

Education level 3 (Advanced/Professional) customers have the highest loan acceptance rate (1920%).

Hence, loan acceptance increases with education level, suggesting that more educated individuals are more likely to take or qualify for a personal loan.

3. Securities Account vs Personal Loan

Customers without a securities account (0) have a loan acceptance rate of about 9.5%.

Those with a securities account (1) have a slightly higher acceptance rate of 11.5%.

Having a securities account shows a positive correlation with personal loan acceptance, possibly reflecting higher financial literacy or investment activity.

4. CD Account vs Personal Loan

A very strong relationship is observed here.

Customers without a CD account (0) have a low loan acceptance rate (7%), while those with a CD account (1) have a very high acceptance rate (46%).

This suggests that holding a CD account is a key indicator of customers more likely to avail personal loans, possibly due to stronger banking relationships or higher financial credibility.

5. Online vs Personal Loan

Loan acceptance rates are similar between those who use online banking and those who dont.

Customers not using online services (0) have a loan acceptance rate of 9.4%, while those using online banking (1) have a slightly higher rate (9.8%).

The impact of online usage on loan acceptance is minimal, indicating it may not be a significant differentiator.

6. CreditCard vs Personal Loan

Customers without a credit card (0) show a loan acceptance rate of 9.5%, and those with a credit card (1) have a similar rate (~9.7%).

This suggests no significant relationship between having a credit card and taking a personal loan.

    plt.subplot(1,2,2)

    plt.title(f'{col} vs {target} (Violin Plot)')
    plt.show()

Observation:

1. Age vs Personal_Loan

The age distribution for both groups (loan taken = 1, loan not taken = 0) is fairly similar.

However, customers who accepted the loan tend to be slightly older on average than those who did not.

The violin plot shows that the median age for loan takers is marginally higher, indicating that middle-aged customers are more likely to take a personal loan.

2. Experience vs Personal_Loan

The experience pattern follows a trend similar to age.

Customers with more years of experience are somewhat more likely to take a loan.

The distribution for non-loan takers is concentrated toward lower experience levels, suggesting that higher professional experience correlates slightly with loan acceptance.

3. Income vs Personal_Loan

A strong positive relationship is visible between income and loan acceptance.

Customers who accepted personal loans have significantly higher incomes, as shown by both boxplot and violin plot.

This indicates that income is a key differentiator higher-income customers are more likely to qualify for or choose personal loans.

4. CCAvg (Credit Card Average Spending) vs Personal_Loan

Customers with higher average monthly credit card spending are much more likely to take a personal loan.

The median CCAvg for loan takers is clearly higher, with a wider distribution extending into higher values.

This suggests that spending behavior is a strong predictor of loan acceptance, as high spenders might need additional credit support.

5. Mortgage vs Personal_Loan

Customers with a higher mortgage value tend to be more likely to take a personal loan.

The median and upper range values for loan takers are higher compared to non-takers.

This suggests that individuals with existing financial liabilities (like mortgages) may also opt for personal loans for liquidity or debt consolidation.

Observation:

The feature Income shows the strongest positive correlation (0.5) with Personal_Loan, indicating that customers with higher income are more likely to accept a personal loan.

CCAvg (Credit Card Average Spending) also shows a moderately strong positive correlation (0.37), suggesting that customers with higher spending behavior are more inclined to take personal loans.

CD_Account has a positive correlation (0.32), implying that customers holding Certificate of Deposit accounts are more likely to have personal loans.

Mortgage (0.14) and Education (0.14) have weak but noticeable positive correlations, meaning customers with higher education and some mortgage obligations may have a slightly higher likelihood of taking personal loans.

Other variables such as Family (0.06), Securities_Account (0.02), Online (0.006), and CreditCard (0.0028) have negligible correlations, indicating minimal influence on loan acceptance.

Features like Age (-0.0077), Experience (-0.014), and ZIPCode (-0.003) show almost no correlation with personal loan decisions.

In[40]:
# Writing the user define function for model prediction and confusion matrix score. 

def train_and_evaluate_model(model):
    model.fit(X_train,y_train)
    y_pred = model.predict(X_test)
    print(classification_report(y_test,y_pred))
    acc = accuracy_score(y_test,y_pred)
    y_pred_train = model.predict(X_train)
    y_pred_test = model.predict(X_test)
    train_acc = accuracy_score(y_train, y_pred_train)
    test_acc = accuracy_score(y_test, y_pred_test)
    print("Train Accuracy:", train_acc)
    print("Test Accuracy:", test_acc)
    precision = precision_score(y_test,y_pred,average='micro')
    recall = recall_score(y_test,y_pred,average='micro')
    f1 = f1_score(y_test,y_pred,average='micro')
    ConfusionMatrixDisplay.from_predictions(y_test,y_pred)
    plt.show();
    model_names.append(model)
    accuracy_scores.append(acc)
    precision_scores.append(precision)
    recall_scores.append(recall)
    f1_scores.append(f1)

Post-Pruning for Decision Tree using Cost Complexity Pruning

In[48]:
# Train an initial (unpruned) Decision Tree
dt = DecisionTreeClassifier(random_state=42)
dt.fit(X_train, y_train)

# Get the pruning path (ccp_alpha values)
path = dt.cost_complexity_pruning_path(X_train, y_train)
ccp_alphas = path.ccp_alphas
impurities = path.impurities

# Plot the pruning path to visualize alpha vs impurity
plt.figure(figsize=(8,4))
plt.plot(ccp_alphas[:-1], impurities[:-1], marker='o', drawstyle="steps-post")
plt.xlabel("Effective Alpha (ccp_alpha)")
plt.ylabel("Total Impurity of Leaves")
plt.title("Cost-Complexity Pruning Path")
plt.show()

# Train multiple trees with different alpha values
clfs = []
for ccp_alpha in ccp_alphas:
    clf = DecisionTreeClassifier(random_state=42, ccp_alpha=ccp_alpha)
    clf.fit(X_train, y_train)
    clfs.append(clf)

# Evaluate train/test accuracy for each alpha
train_scores = [clf.score(X_train, y_train) for clf in clfs]
test_scores = [clf.score(X_test, y_test) for clf in clfs]

# Plot accuracy vs alpha to choose best pruning level
plt.figure(figsize=(8,4))
plt.plot(ccp_alphas, train_scores, marker='o', label='Train Accuracy', drawstyle="steps-post")
plt.plot(ccp_alphas, test_scores, marker='o', label='Test Accuracy', drawstyle="steps-post")
plt.xlabel("ccp_alpha")
plt.ylabel("Accuracy")
plt.legend()
plt.title("Post-Pruning: Accuracy vs ccp_alpha")
plt.show()

# Select the alpha value with highest test accuracy
optimal_alpha = ccp_alphas[np.argmax(test_scores)]
print(f" Optimal ccp_alpha for pruning: {optimal_alpha}")

# Train and evaluate the pruned Decision Tree
pruned_tree = DecisionTreeClassifier(random_state=42, ccp_alpha=optimal_alpha)
train_and_evaluate_model(pruned_tree)

The decision tree now provides transparent and actionable rules, making it suitable for marketing and business strategy teams.

2. Key Decision Drivers

The topmost (root) node of the tree splits on Income 0.54 (normalized scale) indicating that Income is the strongest and primary predictor of personal loan acceptance.

Subsequent splits are based on CCAvg (Credit Card Average Spending), CD_Account, Education, and Family, reaffirming that financial behavior and product holdings drive loan eligibility more than demographics.

3. Important Decision Rules

From the simplified rule set, the models key decision paths can be summarized as:

Rule 1: If Income 0.54 and CCAvg 0.58 No Personal Loan (Class 0) -Represents low-income and low-spending customers who are unlikely to accept a loan.

Rule 2: If Income 0.54 and CCAvg > 0.58 and CD_Account 0.50 No Loan -Even with moderate spending, not having a CD account reduces likelihood of loan acceptance.

Rule 3: If Income 0.54 and CCAvg > 0.58 and CD_Account > 0.50 Loan Accepted (Class 1) -Indicates financially engaged, moderate-income customers with CD accounts are open to loans.

Rule 4: If Income > 0.54 and Education > 1.5 and CCAvg > 0.29 Loan Accepted (Class 1) -Higher-income, well-educated, and high-spending customers are most likely to take a personal loan.

Rule 5: If Income > 0.86 Loan Accepted (Class 1) -High-income customers are almost certain loan prospects, regardless of other attributes.

4. Business Interpretation

Customers with higher income, high credit card spending, and existing CD accounts show strong interest in personal loans.

Education and Family size act as moderate influencers higher education slightly increases acceptance, while larger families slightly decrease it.

The tree reveals clear segmentation between low-income, non-responsive customers and high-value, responsive ones perfect for marketing targeting.

Conclusion & Business Implication

The Post-Pruned Decision Tree provides a clear, rule-based roadmap for identifying ideal personal loan candidates.

Income, CCAvg, and CD_Account are the most influential predictors, and campaigns should focus on high-income, financially active customers.

The simplicity of the model ensures that the marketing and CRM teams can directly apply these decision rules for segmentation and campaign automation.

Complex decision tree, harder to interpret.

we will usse only if we want maximum recall for loan takers (Class 1) and dont mind overfitting.

Easier to interpret and faster to compute.

A good balance for explainability and efficiency.

Model is simplified yet retains predictive strength the ideal outcome of pruning.

Best balance of interpretability, generalization, and accuracy.

Actionable Insights & Recommendations

1. Key Insights from Analysis

Customer Income and Credit Card Spending (CCAvg) are the strongest predictors of Personal Loan acceptance. Customers with higher income and higher average spending are far more likely to take a loan.

Having a Certificate of Deposit (CD) account also strongly correlates with loan uptake, indicating that financially active customers are more open to new banking products.

Mortgage has a moderate positive influence, suggesting customers with existing debt obligations might be open to debt consolidation loans.

Demographic variables such as Age, Experience, and Family size show minimal influence, meaning marketing efforts should focus on financial behavior rather than demographics.

The Post-Pruned Decision Tree Model achieved ~99% accuracy, demonstrating strong reliability in identifying potential loan customers while minimizing false positives.

2. Target Customer Segments

Based on predictive insights:

High-income customers (Income > 100)

High spenders (CCAvg > 3)

Customers holding CD Accounts

Customers with moderate mortgages (100300 range)

These segments represent the most responsive audience for personal loan offers.

3. Marketing Strategy Recommendations

a. Personalized Campaigns

Design targeted campaigns for customers identified by the model (high-income, high-spending, or CD account holders).

Use personalized offers such as lower interest rates or quick approval for these high-potential leads.

b. Cross-Sell to Existing Customers

Focus on customers who already use CD Accounts or Credit Cards, as they have shown a higher loan acceptance rate.

Offer bundled financial products, such as Loan + Savings or Loan + CD Renewal Bonus.

c. Digital and Email Marketing

Leverage the Online banking users segment for email or app-based campaigns, promoting convenience and instant eligibility checks.

Use AI-based targeting or CRM segmentation using the models predictions for maximum conversion efficiency.

d. Customer Education

For educated or financially savvy customers (Education level 2 or 3), highlight investment potential and flexibility of personal loans rather than just credit access.

For lower-education segments, focus on simple and trust-based communication.

e. Reduce False Negatives

Customers who are likely to take a loan but are not targeted (false negatives) represent missed opportunities.

Run follow-up marketing to re-engage such customers through personalized phone calls or SMS offers.
